<p><a name="punctuation-note" id="punctuation-note"></a></p>
<h1 id="toc0"><span><a href="#punctuation">Non-ASCII Punctuation</a></span></h1>
<table class="wiki-content-table"><tr><th>unicode name</th>
<th>ascii approximation</th>
<th>unicode</th>
<th>html entity</th>
</tr><tr><td>left single quotation mark<br />
right single quotation mark</td>
<td>0027: '<br />
0027: '</td>
<td>2018: ‘<br />
2019: ’</td>
<td>&amp;lsquo;<br />
&amp;rsquo;</td>
</tr><tr><td>left double quotation mark<br />
right double quotation mark</td>
<td>0022: "<br />
0022: "</td>
<td>201C: “<br />
201D: ”</td>
<td>&amp;ldquo;<br />
&amp;rdquo;</td>
</tr><tr><td>prime</td>
<td>0027: '</td>
<td>2032: ′</td>
<td>&amp;prime;</td>
</tr><tr><td>double prime</td>
<td>0022: "</td>
<td>2033: ″</td>
<td>&amp;Prime;</td>
</tr><tr><td>en dash</td>
<td>002D 002D: <span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">--</span></td>
<td>2013: –</td>
<td>&amp;ndash;</td>
</tr><tr><td>em dash</td>
<td>002D 002D 002D: <span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">---</span></td>
<td>2014: —</td>
<td>&amp;mdash;</td>
</tr><tr><td>horizontal ellipsis</td>
<td>002E 002E 002E: <span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">...</span></td>
<td>2026: …</td>
<td>&amp;hellip;</td>
</tr><tr><td>minus sign</td>
<td>002D: -</td>
<td>2212: −</td>
<td>&amp;minus;</td>
</tr><tr><td>multiplication sign</td>
<td>002A: *</td>
<td>00D7: ×</td>
<td>&amp;times;</td>
</tr><tr><td>division sign</td>
<td>002F: /</td>
<td>00F7: ÷</td>
<td>&amp;divide;</td>
</tr></table><p>The ASCII character set omitted punctuation marks that are necessary to properly typeset English. It was able to do this because there were already typewriter conventions for representing the missing characters.</p>
<p>Prime and double prime are most often used as abbreviated units of measurement for feet and inches.</p>
<p>Em dash is used to mark an incomplete or interrupted sentence. It is used to mark off an utterance that is interjected into a sentence as an aside.</p>
<p>En dash is used to indicate a range of values. It separates the first and the last value and the other values are omitted.</p>
<p>The hyphen is used to join nouns into a compound noun. In English one must consult a dictionary to determine if the components of a compound noun are separated by spaces, hyphens, or nothing. The minus sign is the symbol for subtraction. The name for U+002D is <em>hyphen-minus</em>, suggesting that it correct to use the symbol for either. Unicode has separate character U+2212 called <em>minus sign</em>, however.</p>
<p><em>combining and non-combining versions of prime and double prime</em></p>
<p>If one is not limited to ASCII and wants to produce typographically correct punctuation, consider entering the punctuation explicitly. Some software will infer typographically correct punctuation from ASCII approximations, but the software tends to be a headache in contexts such as software documentation.</p>
<p><a name="markdown" id="markdown"></a></p>
<h1 id="toc1"><span><a href="#top">Markdown</a></span></h1>
<p><a href="http://daringfireball.net/projects/markdown/syntax">Markdown</a></p>
<p>Markdown was developed in 2004. The first implementation was in Perl. It is used by Tumblr, Stackoverflow, and Reddit. Here is a <a href="http://daringfireball.net/projects/markdown/dingus">sandbox</a>.</p>
<p>On Ubuntu you can install a script which converts Markdown to HTML with the following command:</p>
<div class="code">
<pre>
<code>sudo apt-get install markdown</code>
</pre></div>
<p>It is a Perl script. If you copy it over to a Mac it will probably work as long as the necessary Perl module (Text::Markdown) is installed.</p>
<p>The command line script converts Markdown to HTML. Invoke it like this:</p>
<div class="code">
<pre>
<code>$ markdown foo.md &gt; foo.html</code>
</pre></div>
<p><a name="pandoc" id="pandoc"></a></p>
<h1 id="toc2"><span><a href="#top">Pandoc</a></span></h1>
<p><a href="http://johnmacfarlane.net/pandoc/README.html">Pandoc User's Guide</a><br /><a href="http://johnmacfarlane.net/pandoc/README.html#pandocs-markdown">Pandoc's Markdown</a></p>
<p>There are installers for <a href="http://code.google.com/p/pandoc/downloads/list">Windows and Mac</a>. On Ubuntu Pandoc can be installed with</p>
<div class="code">
<pre>
<code>sudo apt-get install pandoc</code>
</pre></div>
<p>Pandoc can read Markdown, LaTeX, HTML, and a few other formats. It can output HTML, RTF, MediaWiki Syntax, groff man page format, Emacs Org-Mode, AsciiDoc, EPub, GNU Texinfo, Word docx, Slidy, and some other formats.</p>
<p>Pandoc's version of Markdown has extensions. Using the extensions avoids HTML and makes it easier for Pandoc to target other formats.</p>
<p><a name="pandoc-header-identifiers" id="pandoc-header-identifiers"></a></p>
<h2 id="toc3"><span>header identifiers</span></h2>
<p><a href="http://johnmacfarlane.net/pandoc/README.html#header-identifiers-in-html-latex-and-context">pandoc header identifiers</a></p>
<p>If the rule for generating a header identifier results in all characters being removed, the first unused identifier from the following sequence is used:</p>
<ul><li>section</li>
<li>section-1</li>
<li>section-2</li>
<li>…</li>
</ul><p><a name="pandoc-delimited-code-block" id="pandoc-delimited-code-block"></a></p>
<h2 id="toc4"><span>delimited code block</span></h2>
<p><a href="http://johnmacfarlane.net/pandoc/README.html#delimited-code-blocks">delimited code blocks</a></p>
<p>The tildes which terminate the block must be at least as numerous as the tildes which started it. This provides a mechanism for putting code which contains a line of tildes inside the code block.</p>
<p>The following markup will number the lines starting from 100:</p>
<div class="code">
<pre>
<code>~~~ {.C .numberLines startFrom="100"}
int add(int a, int b) {
  return (a+b);
}
~~~</code>
</pre></div>
<p><a name="restructured-text" id="restructured-text"></a></p>
<h1 id="toc5"><span><a href="#top">reStructuredText</a></span></h1>
<p><a href="http://docutils.sourceforge.net/docs/ref/rst/restructuredtext.html">reStructuredText Markup Specification</a></p>
<p><a name="mediawiki" id="mediawiki"></a></p>
<h1 id="toc6"><span><a href="#top">MediaWiki</a></span></h1>
<p><a href="http://www.mediawiki.org/wiki/Help:Formatting">MediaWiki Syntax</a></p>
<p>MediaWiki powers Wikipedia and the wikifarm Wikia. The source code is freely available.</p>
<p>MediaWiki 1.19 includes a script called maintenance/parse.php which can be used to render MediaWiki markup on the command line.</p>
<p>Wikipedia was launched in January 2001. The site initially used wiki software implemented in Perl called UseModWiki. In January 2002 the site switched to custom software written in PHP. The PHP code was rewritten for scalability in July 2002. It was given the name MediaWiki in 2003 and was eventually open sourced.</p>
<p>UseModWiki had a spare set of markup which did not expand much on the markup used by Wiki Base, the original wiki software used by WikiWikiWeb.</p>
<table class="wiki-content-table"><tr><th></th>
<th><a href="http://c2.com/cgi/wiki?TextFormattingRules">Wiki Base</a> (1995)</th>
<th><a href="http://www.usemod.com/cgi-bin/wiki.pl?TextFormattingRules">UseModWiki</a> (1999)</th>
<th>MediaWiki (2002)</th>
</tr><tr><td><span style="color: darkblue"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">link</span></span></td>
